**Generating a Table of Contents in LaTeX**
=====================================================

LaTeX provides a built-in mechanism to generate a table of contents (TOC) automatically. Here's an example of how to do it:

### Step 1: Include the `tocloft` package

To generate a table of contents, you need to include the `tocloft` package in your LaTeX document. Add the following line to your preamble:

```latex
\usepackage{tocloft}
```

### Step 2: Create a table of contents

To create a table of contents, use the `\tableofcontents` command. This command should be placed after the `\begin{document}` command, but before the first section or chapter.

```latex
\documentclass{book}
\usepackage{tocloft}

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\chapter{Chapter 1}
\section{Section 1.1}
\section{Section 1.2}

\chapter{Chapter 2}
\section{Section 2.1}
\section{Section 2.2}

\end{document}
```

### Step 3: Customize the table of contents (optional)

You can customize the table of contents by using various options provided by the `tocloft` package. For example, you can change the font size, spacing, and formatting of the table of contents entries.

```latex
\renewcommand{\cftchapfont}{\large}
\renewcommand{\cftsecfont}{\large}
\renewcommand{\cftsubsecfont}{\large}

\setlength{\cftbeforechapskip}{1em}
\setlength{\cftbeforesecskip}{0.5em}
\setlength{\cftbeforesubsecskip}{0.25em}
```

### Step 4: Use the `minitoc` package for sub-TOCs (optional)

If you have a large document with many chapters and sections, you may want to include a mini table of contents at the beginning of each chapter. The `minitoc` package provides this functionality.

```latex
\usepackage{minitoc}

\dominitoc
\dominitoc[chapter]
```

This will generate a mini table of contents at the beginning of each chapter.

### Example Use Case

